      <abstract displayLabel="Abstract">Simulation and optimization must be used together to design and
                operate large-scale, complex systems. Integrating them presents a number of
                conceptual and technical problems, which can be addressed with more expressive,
                computer-interpretable system models. This paper presents a model-driven approach to
                integrating simulation and optimization methods by exchanging system designs that
                specialize analysis abstractions, both defined in the Systems Modeling Language
                (SysML). The analysis abstractions enable translation of system models to
                corresponding analysis models and tool interfaces. This approach (model-driven
                system-analysis integration) is demonstrated by developing a multi-fidelity,
                multi-method simulation optimization methodology and applying it to a supply chain
                design case study.</abstract>
